    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="732"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.51/58</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Halifax</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide-Mémoire</hi>
                </p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Ambassador presents his compliments to the Secretary of State, and
                    has the honour to refer to the Department’s <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                    of November 29th last<note n="46" xml:id="d732fn46">
                        <ref target="frus1943v04#pg_914">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 914</ref>.</note> suggesting that
                    immediate consideration be given to ways and means whereby the British and
                    United States Governments might assist the Government of Saudi Arabia in fiscal
                    and currency problems, and that informal discussion to this end be held in
                    Washington.</p>
                <pb facs="0686" n="674" xml:id="pg_674"/>
                <p>2. His Majesty’s Government in the United Kingdom agree to this proposal, and
                    instructions have been issued to the United Kingdom Treasury Delegation in
                    Washington to get in touch with representatives of the United States Treasury to
                    this end.<note n="47" xml:id="d732fn47">Meetings of officers from the
                        Department, the Treasury Department, and the British Embassy began on
                        February 17, 1944, and continued through much of the year.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-01">February 1,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
